<div class="comment" id="c_1713661081">
	<div>
		<img src="//a.disquscdn.com/1611874952/images/noavatar32.png" class="comment_author_profile_pic">
	</div>
	<div>
		<div class="comment_header">
		Comment <a href="#c_1713661081">9</a> by Neil Bailey
		posted on 1/6/2007 at 1:44 AM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>This is almost my point exactly.  Ajax not only 'does the trick' for us, it does it WELL.  Its fast, and our code is well organized and straightforward.</p><p>AjaxCFC allows us to pass EXTREMELY complex data structures back and forth between our front-end page and our back-end CFC - and it does this completely without any kind of configuring on our end.  The ONLY reason I can even imagine anyone using Flex would be for the UI capabilities, and for that you can use YUI, DOJO, QooXDoo, or any of a number of JS UI packages.  And all of these come *without any additional overhead* - this is an EXTREMELY important point.</p><p>I have been asking the *exact* same question ever since CFUNITED last year, and have never - not ONCE - gotten a decent answer:  why would I use Flex instead of CF/Ajax?  Not some, "there are places for both yada yad yada yada" but a *firm* WHY.</p><p>Anyone?</p></div>
	</div>
</div>
		
<div class="comment" id="c_1713661078">
	<div>
		<img src="//a.disquscdn.com/1611874952/images/noavatar32.png" class="comment_author_profile_pic">
	</div>
	<div>
		<div class="comment_header">
		Comment <a href="#c_1713661078">10</a> by Brian Rinaldi
		posted on 1/6/2007 at 1:58 AM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>While I think it is odd that this has somehow turned into a Flex vs Ajax debate - must it always end this way :\ - in my opinion you are turning the argument upside-down and that is why you have never seen an answer you like. First, Flex isn't just about passing data (which is all AjaxCFC handles) but about a rich UI. Yes, you can do this with a bunch of different libraries in Ajax, but this is notoriously complex, and often very poorly documented. Also, Ajax can be extremely difficult to debug.</p><p>If you actually tried using Flex 2 (which has minimal overhead that you are so obsessed with - I have used plenty of very slow Ajax apps), I think the conclusion you would come to is, you use Flex wherever possible and Ajax only when the Flash 9 requirement would be onerous.</p><p>The Flex UI is *far* richer than anything I have seen done in Ajax (and don't get me wrong I have seen some really sweet Ajax apps that I use daily and I have done some nice stuff with Ajax myself). It supports automatically translating native CF data types - including CFCs. I mean seriously, the only argument here is because you don't want to be convinced...which is perfectly ok if you are happy with the way you do things, but you seem to want others to be forced to agree with you and accept that because you didn't like the CFUnited presentation this is somehow an argument against Flex...</p><p>Go on...do what you do...Ajax is very cool and very useful and if you insist on not being convinced of Flex, that is fine, but can we drop the argument?</p></div>
	</div>
</div>
		
<div class="comment" id="c_1713661085">
	<div>
		<img src="//a.disquscdn.com/1611874952/images/noavatar32.png" class="comment_author_profile_pic">
	</div>
	<div>
		<div class="comment_header">
		Comment <a href="#c_1713661085">11</a> by Neil Bailey
		posted on 1/6/2007 at 2:06 AM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>Haha I didn't mind the presentation at all at CFUNITED.  And its not that I don't want to be convinced - when I first saw Flex, I thought I was in love.  I agree - the UI capabilities are simply insane!</p><p>However...that being said, the overhead costs are, in my opinion, prohibitive.</p><p>Yes, achieving decent UI with JS libraries can be a pain in the.....behind.  If the overhead issues went away, I would move to flex tomorrow.  I just can't justify a trade-off to my employer or our users.  I think (and again, this is just my humble opinion) that the typical user would rather lose a bit of the UI glamor, and at the same time speed up the application's load time - in some cases *dramatically*.</p><p>If I have sounded like I am trying to simply rain on Adobe's parade here, I apologize - seriously.  I LOVE ColdFusion, and again, noone was more in love with the Flash Forms (and then, when it was released, Flex) than I was.</p><p>But that friggin load time kills me every time.  I just can't get around it.  I have seen flex apps that take 30, 35 seconds just to LOAD!  Let me be the one to tell you this - if your app takes 35 seconds to load, you user left 25 - 28 seconds ago.</p></div>
	</div>
</div>
		
<div class="comment" id="c_1713661083">
	<div>
		<img src="//a.disquscdn.com/1611874952/images/noavatar32.png" class="comment_author_profile_pic">
	</div>
	<div>
		<div class="comment_header">
		Comment <a href="#c_1713661083">12</a> by Brian Rinaldi
		posted on 1/6/2007 at 2:22 AM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>I am not pissed and don't think you are raining on anyone's parade, I just find it difficult to argue a point when someone is asking to be convinced of something they are already convinced of...these things go in circles.</p><p>Anyway, in response to your biggest concern about load times:</p><p>Flex 1.5 admittedly had horrible load times, but this is no longer the case in 2. First off, you can deploy directly as a SWF (and I believe this is the recommended deployment - anyway, FDS is required to do otherwise), so the app caches locally and really doesn't load that slowly in the first place. Does this mean it is as fast as an Ajax app?...well, sometimes perhaps, but probably in the usual case, no. However, the load times are fast enough that when a rich UI is needed, then use Flex. If you are doing some simple asynchronous functionality that wouldn't benefit from the UI, use Ajax.</p><p>On a somewhat related note, I personally think that the tendency to deploy Flex apps as full-page will slow and there will be more widgets built into pages where needed (this may already be happening on a grand scale but in general all the apps I see are full-pagers). I think this will also contribute to making it easier to include Flex apps in your average consumer facing page.</p></div>
	</div>
</div>
		
<div class="comment" id="c_1713661082">
